s of the Codex Borgia. These texts were sent to Spain as evidence of failed Dominican evangelization efforts, and there they remained, in oblivion, until the 1960s. In this book, David Tavárez dives deep into this formidable archive of ritual and divinatory manuals, the largest calendar corpus in the colonial Americas, and emerges with a rich understanding of Indigenous social and cultural history, Mesoamerican theories of cosmos and time, and Zapotec ancestor worship. Drawing on his knowledge of Zapotec and Nahuatl, two decades of archival research, and a decade of fieldwork, Tavárez dissects Mesoamerican calendars as well as Native resistance and accommodation to the colonial conquest of time, while also addressing entangled transatlantic histories and shining new light on texts still connected to contemporary observances in Zapotec communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aManuscripts, Zapotec. 0aReligious calendars. 0aZapotec IndiansxAntiquities. 0aZapotec IndiansxHistory. 0aZapotec IndiansxSocial life and customs. 0aZapotec cosmology. 0aZapotec languagexWriting. 0aZapotec mythologyvCalendars. 0aZapotec mythologyxCalendars. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  azapotec, Mesoamerican, Mesoamerica, cosmology, Mesoamerican history, Nahuatl, pre-Columbian.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076651640uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32451640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477324523423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477324523/original  a978-3-11-076651-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EB